<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="GREEN"><I>Rig Veda</I>, tr. by Ralph T.H. Griffith, [1896], at sacred-texts.com</FONT></P><HR></p>  <h3 align="center" align="center">HYMN LXVII. Mitra-Varu&#7751;a.</h3>  
<p>1. YE Gods, &#256;dityas, Varu&#7751;a, Aryaman, Mitra, verily<br> Have here obtained supremest sway, high, holy, set apart for you.<br> 2 When, Varu&#7751;a and Mitra, ye sit in your golden dwelling-place,<br> Ye Twain, supporters of mankind, foeslayers, give felicity.<br> 3 All these, possessors of all wealth, Varu&#7751;a, Mitra, Aryaman,<br> Follow their ways, as if with feet, and guard from injury mortal man.<br> 4 For they are true, they cleave to Law, held holy among every race,<br> Good leaders, bounteous in their gifts, deliverers even from distress.<br> 5 Which of your persons, Varu&#7751;a or Mitra, merits not our praise?<br> Therefore our thought is turned to you, the Atris' thought is turned to you.</p>  
